  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DEC funded emergency assistance to Ukrainian refugees arriving in Romania</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since Russia invaded Ukraine, half a million Ukrainians have arrived in Romania. 

The European Union&#x2019;s Temporary Protection Mechanism (TPM) was legislated in Romania on 23rd March 2022. The TPM allows people fleeing Ukraine, who hold a biometric passport or other valid ID card, to temporarily reside in European Union member states and access key services, without applying for full asylum. This status is valid for one year and grants the right to work, enrol children in school, receive free, basic medical provision, get access to shelter and basic subsistence food and hygiene items in kind. However, both the Romanian authorities and civil society have recognised that the package of assistance offered by Romania under the TPM is not sufficient, and does not allow a dignified and safe existence for refugees in Romania given the heightened risks for vulnerable women and children which exist across Eastern Europe and in the wake of any conflict. 

This 5 month project is part of CAFOD&apos;s Ukraine crisis DEC Phase 1 programme and intends to fill the gaps left by the TPM. It will provide shelter, living allowance, communications and legal advice to Ukrainians arriving in Romania.</narrative>
  </description>
